pr_review_comment_body:
``hangups.channel.Channel._longpoll_request()`` uses ``.request()`` of the new ``http_utils.ClientSession``, which need to be bridge then as well.

As [``aiohttp.ClientSession.get()``](https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/master/aiohttp/client.py#L478..L483
) calls the private ``_request`` method directly instead of calling the public one ``request``, the proxy and header must to be added in the private method.

Hi,

I am not that keen on this idea.

It would be easy to do something like:

    def LineModel(BaseModel):

        def estimate(self, data):

	    if data.shape[1] == 2:
		    self._model = LineModel2D
	    else:
		    self._model = LineModel3D
		
	    self._model.estimate(data)
	    self.params = self._model.params

However, I do not like the fact that LineModel2D has predict_x() and predict_y() functions, which LineModel3D has not. So combining them becomes awkward. Also, one model stores a line as (offset, theta) while the other stores (point, unit vector). So the unique LineModel should specify in its documentation that `params` do not have the same meaning in 2D and in 3D. Hence the rest of the code cannot be unaware of the fact it is written either for 2D or 3D.

While I agree in calling LineModel2D the current LineModel, I do not agree on making a single LineModel that would have different behaviours in 2D or 3D.

I know that we usually use it as hexed (base16), but I would rather keep it as 16-bytes array and do the base16 conversion when needed. Reasons:
* Save space;
* gRPC binary encoding uses the 16-bytes array;

Can we unroll this comprehension into a small stand alone utility function for better readability as well as easier stand-alone testing.

```python
@to_tuple
def (tx, pending_transactions):
    for transaction in pending_transactions:
        ...
        yield transaction
```

Something that's got the same logic, but unrolled into an easier to read code body.

